Tasks in progress

  1. Mapping of crime data from the year 2008-2016 using longitude and lattitude to chicago Zip codes. For the data before 2008, lonitude and lattitude are not available.

  2. Demographic data download from SocialExplorer is complete. One of the challenge is that only 5 year estimates are available (not yearly). Data downloaded for the period 2010-2014 at zip code level. Challenge being Zip code filter not available for the period 2005-2009. Hence mapping from census tract to zipcode is required and is in progress.

  3. Created Yearly and Monthly Time series for business enteries and business exits from the Business Licenses data source. Analysis in progres to identify the right p,d,q,P,D,Q paramter for both the TS. Next steps is to build a cointegration model.

  4. Analysis of business entries plus active in progress.

  5. Analysis of economic factors to analyze the peaks in the Entry and exit time series, as seen from the below plots.

  6. Data preparation for Age of business model is in progress.

ACF and PACF plots

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
acf(Entry.yearly.TS)
pacf(Entry.yearly.TS)

adf.test(Entry.yearly.TS)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  Entry.yearly.TS
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.4182, Lag order = 2, p-value = 0.4131
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

P-value returned from adf.test is 0.4131 which is greater than significance level of 0.01 and 0.05. Hence we cannot reject the null hypothesis that the series is a unit root. Business entry TS is non-stationary

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
acf(Exit.yearly.TS)
pacf(Exit.yearly.TS)

adf.test(Exit.yearly.TS)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  Exit.yearly.TS
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.4504, Lag order = 2, p-value = 0.7817
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

P-value is 0.7817 which is greater than the significance level of 0.01 and 0.05. We can conclude that Business Exit TS is non-stationary.

Function to calculate p,d,q,P,D,Q parameters:

fun.ts.holdout=function(data,nperiod,nstart,prange,drange,qrange,Prange,Drange,Qrange) {

expandedgrid=expand.grid(prange,drange,qrange,Prange,Drange,Qrange)    
            
        rsquares = rep(0,nrow(expandedgrid))
        errors = rep(0,nrow(expandedgrid))
        
        for(i in 1:nrow(expandedgrid)) {
        
            p = expandedgrid[i,1]
            d = expandedgrid[i,2]
            q = expandedgrid[i,3]
            P = expandedgrid[i,4]
            D = expandedgrid[i,5]
            Q = expandedgrid[i,6]
            
            tmp = fun.illustrate.3(data,nperiod,nstart,p,d,q,P,D,Q)
            rsquares[i]=tmp$Average.Rsquare
            errors[i]=tmp$Average.Error
        }
        
        return(list(rsquares = rsquares, errors=errors, pdqPDQvalues=expandedgrid ,
                    minerror=which(errors == min(errors))))
}

fun.illustrate.3=function(data,nperiod,nstart,p,d,q,P,D,Q) {
        
        rsquare.holdout = rep(0,nperiod)
        error.holdout = rep(0,nperiod)
        for(i in 2:nperiod) {
            cutoff=length(data)-i
            yvec.train=as.vector(data)[1:cutoff]
            yvec.hold=as.vector(data)[(cutoff+1):length(data)]
            y=ts(yvec.train,start=nstart, frequency=1)
            pred=predict(arima(y, order = c(p,d,q),
                               seasonal = list(order = c(P,D,Q)),method = "CSS"),
                         n.ahead=(length(data)-cutoff))
            error.holdout[i]=mean((pred$pred-yvec.hold)^2)
            if(i>1) {rsquare.holdout[i]=(cor(pred$pred,yvec.hold))^2}
        }
        return(list(rsquare.holdout=rsquare.holdout, error.holdout=error.holdout, 
                    Average.Error = mean(error.holdout),
                    Average.Rsquare=mean(rsquare.holdout,na.rm=TRUE),
                    p=p,q=q,d=d,P=P,Q=Q,D=D) )
}
